I would prefer the solution without the immutability-helper since I find this much more readable. An example for that can be found in src/reducers/build.js. I also have the plan to remove this additional dependency completely, but I didn't find the time to do so yet. Most of the functions we use from that package can also be done quite easily with plain javascript.

Basically, we just have to change the update() call and use the spread operator (...) instead to copy the old state and extend/overwrite certain values:

return {
  ...state,
  isFetching: false,
}

or 

return {
  ...state,
  autoholds: action.autoholds,
  isFetching: false,
}
